   "source": [
    "# Machine Learning Model on Refugee Population Forecasting and Humanitarian Resource Planning System for Kenya\n",
    "___\n",
    "**Team**: XG BOOST BUSTERS  \n",
    "**Contributors**: Cynthia Jemutai, Stephen Jilani, Charity Nduati,Joy Njeru , Chris Karagu , Sylvia  Wambui\n",
    "\n",
    "**Project**: Phase 5 Capstone Project   \n",
    "**Data Sources**: [Kenya Refugee and Asylum Population Dataset](https://www..com/)\n",
    "___"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0e1021f2",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "0e1021f2"
   },
   "source": [
    "### 1. Introduction"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "306cff84",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "306cff84"
   },
   "source": [
    "Kenya accommodates populations displaced by conflict, persecution, climate shocks, and political instability originating from across the region including Somalia, South Sudan, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Burundi, and Rwanda, among 39 origin countries identified in this dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "Several organizations work together to support refugees in Kenya:\n",
    "1. **Department of Refugee Services (DRS)**: The Kenyan government agency responsible for refugee registration, camp management, policy implementation, and ensuring compliance with the Refugee Act of 2021.\n",
    "2. **United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)**: Coordinates the overall refugee response, manages refugee registration and data, mobilizes international funding, and promotes refugee protection.\n",
    "3. **World Food Programme (WFP)**: Provides food assistance through food distribution and Cash and Voucher Assistance (CVA) programmes to improve food security.\n",
    "4. **Kenya Red Cross Society (KRCS)**: Delivers frontline humanitarian services, including emergency medical care, disaster response, water supply, family tracing, and support for new refugee arrivals at border entry points.\n",
    "\n",
    "Together, these organizations form an integrated humanitarian system that provides protection, food, healthcare, and essential services to refugees across Kenya."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c7089c51",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "c7089c51"
   },
   "source": [
    "### 2. Problem Statement"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "870785db",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "870785db"
   },
   "source": [
    "Kenya hosts one of the largest refugee populations in sub-Saharan Africa, making effective humanitarian planning essential. However, resource planning is often based on current or historical population data rather than future forecasts, limiting preparedness for sudden increases in refugee arrivals.\n",
    "\n",
    "Key challenges identified from the HDX HAPI dataset include:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Rapid population changes that increase demand for food, healthcare, shelter, and other essential services.\n",
    "2. Diverse demographic groups with different ages, genders, and vulnerabilities that require tailored support.\n",
    "3. Different population categories (e.g., refugees and asylum seekers) with distinct humanitarian needs.\n",
    "4. Delays in resource deployment, making it difficult to respond quickly to population surges.\n",
    "5. Limited use of historical data for forecasting despite decades of available records.\n",
    "\n",
    "These challenges highlight the need for a machine learning-based forecasting approach to support better resource planning and decision-making for refugee assistance in Kenya."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68589f20",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "68589f20"
   },
   "source": [
    "### 3. Project Objectives"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1d9fc12",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "e1d9fc12"
   },
   "source": [
    "#### 3.1 Primary Objective\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "90f89e36",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "90f89e36"
   },
   "source": [
    "To design, develop, and validate a machine learning forecasting system that predicts Kenya's refugee and asylum-seeker population levels disaggregated by origin country, population group, gender, and age cohort with a forecasting horizon of 6 to 24 months, and to translate these forecasts into quantified humanitarian resource planning recommendations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "79904035",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "79904035"
   },
   "source": [
    "#### 3.2 Specific Objectives\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d8129bfc",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "d8129bfc"
   },
   "source": [
    "1. Explore the HDX HAPI Kenya dataset to identify population trends, demographic patterns, and changes over time.\n",
    "2. Create relevant features to improve forecasting performance.\n",
    "3. Develop and compare forecasting models to predict refugee population trends.\n",
    "4. Generate population forecasts by refugee category, age, gender, and country of origin.\n",
    "5. Estimate humanitarian resource needs based on the forecasted population.\n",
    "6. Evaluate model performance using standard forecasting metrics (RMSE, MAE, and MAPE).\n",
    "7. Provide recommendations to support data-driven humanitarian planning and decision-making in Kenya."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c853695e",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "c853695e"
   },
   "source": [
    "### 4. Data Understanding\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "26010573",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "26010573"
   },
   "source": [
    "The dataset used for this project is the Kenya Refugee and Asylum Population Dataset, obtained from the Humanitarian Data Exchange (HDX) platform.The dataset contains historical records of displaced populations hosted in Kenya and provides detailed demographic information necessary for forecasting refugee population trends and supporting humanitarian resource planning.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset covers a 25-year period from 2001 to 2025, containing 27,664 records and 15 variables. Each record represents a population observation reported for a specific period, location, population category, gender, and age group.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset includes four main population groups:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Refugees (REF)**: Individuals who have been recognized as refugees and require international protection.\n",
    "2. **Asylum Seekers (ASY)**: Individuals who have applied for refugee status and are awaiting determination.\n",
    "3. **Host Community (HST)**: Members of the local population affected by refugee presence and humanitarian operations.\n",
    "4. **Others of Concern (OOC)**: Individuals who require humanitarian assistance but do not fall under the refugee or asylum seeker categories.\n",
    "\n",
    "The main target variable for this project is:\n",
    "\n",
    "**Population**: The recorded number of individuals within each demographic category. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Key predictor variables**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Column | Description |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| reference_period_start / end | Reporting period boundaries |\n",
    "| asylum_location_code | Country where asylum is provided |\n",
    "| origin_location_code | Country of origin of displaced population |\n",
    "| population_group | Refugee population category |\n",
    "| gender | Gender category (male/female) |\n",
    "| age_range | Age cohort category |\n",
    "| min_age / max_age | Age boundaries of the cohort |\n",
    "| population | Number of individuals recorded (target) |\n",
    "\n",
    "he dataset is well suited to this project because it contains long-term historical observations, demographic breakdowns, and population movement patterns required for machine learning forecasting."
   ]
  },
